The Trojan horse of Europe
BERKELEY – Europe will have no choice but to bail out Greece.
Funds will need to be provided urgently.
Conditions will need to be attached.
The Greek government will make the usual promises.
This should allow the Greek government to service its debt.
The markets will calm down.
The longer-term consequences will not be catastrophic, but there will be problems ahead.
Some will say that the fatal mistake was allowing Greece to adopt the euro in the first place.
It was nevertheless already clear that the country was not ready.
Its budget policy was already out of control when it joined the monetary union in 2001, and its unions were already pressing for Greek wages to align with those practiced in Europe, despite lower productivity.
But this response is too simplistic, as such signs of dysfunction do not limit themselves to Greece.
Spain, with a 20% unemployment rate and abyssal budget deficits, sees Greece as an image of its own future.
And if that is not the case, the markets will take care of it.
Portugal and Italy are doing a bit better.
These countries, just like Greece, must face significant budget cuts.
Like Greece, they cannot devalue their currency to encourage exports.
Like Greece, they must deal with a deep recession.
Like Greece, they will be tempted to seek aid.
All of this raises one question: was the real mistake not creating the euro?
Since I was one of the few Americans to encourage the idea of a European currency, you might ask: are you reconsidering your initial stance?
No, creating the euro was not an error, but it could well become one.
The Greek crisis shows that Europe is only halfway towards a viable monetary union.
If it does nothing, the next crisis could make this seem like a walk in the park.
If it wants to complete its monetary union, Europe must create its own emergency funding mechanism.
Today, members of the Union can only help Greece by overriding regulations that prevent them from granting an exception loan except in the case of natural disasters or circumstances beyond a country's control.
This exacerbates uncertainty.
When European leaders provide aid, public opinion and markets tend to question their honesty.
If the problems stem from the Lisbon Treaty, then it needs to be amended.
Moreover, aid should not be granted solely under certain conditions but should be accompanied by temporary control of the national budget by a committee of "experts" appointed by the European Union.
The history shows that simple promises made by beneficiary countries are not enough.
Of course, the countries that will be subject to such measures will express their indignation.
But, no one forces them to accept this money.
Moral considerations?
Here is your solution.
Note that this would be a much more effective disciplinary mechanism than the defunct Stability and Growth Pact.
We could also ask the following question: how would Californians react if their state temporarily placed its budget in the hands of an expert specially appointed by the administration of President Barack Obama?
In fact, they would not be bothered by this very much.
The expert would not be of California origin, but American.
The public would understand that he would act in the interest of the California state as well as the country.
The fact that California sends representatives to Washington, where these orders would emanate from this expert, would reassure them.
Europeans do not do this kind of thing because they first and foremost consider themselves as Greeks and Germans.
They do not interfere with the "sovereignty prerogatives" of other member states.
Germany is particularly reluctant given its history during World War II, especially in Greece.
If Europe really wants to achieve its monetary union, it will have to overcome its past.
This union implies not only stronger economic ties but also closer political bonds.
Those who have a solid emergency aid mechanism will really have to be accountable.
They will have to answer to a strong European Parliament.
The electorate of German Chancellor Angela Merkel hates this kind of rescue because they know very well who will pay for it.
The Germans oppose anything that resembles political European integration.
But Germany has its share of responsibility in this crisis.
It wanted an incredibly independent central bank that was not accountable, but today it has adopted a monetary policy that is too excessive, thereby contributing critically to worsening the situation of the PIIGS (Portugal, Ireland, Italy, Greece, and Spain).
The huge current account surpluses of Germany further exacerbate their situation.
Moreover, its fiscal stimulus measures were not sufficient to support the European economy.
Germany has significantly benefited from the creation of the euro.
It should do the same.
It should encourage the creation of an emergency lending facility, as well as political integration to make it possible.
It must provide more budgetary support.
Is it not best positioned to exert pressure for a more responsible European Central Bank?
The Greek crisis could be the Trojan horse that will lead Europe towards greater political integration.
We can only hope so.
